{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Montserrat", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Montserrat}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Montserrat\n| map1 = File:Montserrat map from CIA World Factbook.png\n| places = \n| legend1 =\n| map2 = \n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Montserrat]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 18 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=18|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| confirmed_cases = 11<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/montserrat-goes-second-week-with-no-new-cases-of-covid-19/|title=MONTSERRAT GOES SECOND WEEK WITH NO NEW CASES OF COVID-19|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref> (2020-04-25)\n| suspected_cases =\n| recovery_cases = 2\n| deaths = 1\n| total_ili =\n| website = [http://www.gov.ms gov.ms]\n}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] in Montserrat''' is part of the ongoing global [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|viral pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), which was confirmed to have reached the [[British Overseas Territory]] of [[Montserrat]] on 17 March 2020.<ref name=\"first\"/>. The first death occurred on 24 April 2020.<ref name=\"first_death\"/>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" />\n\nThe island had a population of 4,649 people in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/FINAL-REPORT-KEY-FINDINGS-CENSUS-LABOUR-FORCE-SURVEY-2018-.pdf|title=MONTSERRAT STATISTICS DEPARTMENT LABOUR FORCE CENSUS|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref> Testing for Covid-19 is being performed by the [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/positive-covid-19-cases-on-montserrat-increase-to-eight/|title=POSITIVE COVID-19 CASES ON MONTSERRAT INCREASE TO EIGHT|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===March 2020===\nOn 18 March, the first case in Montserrat was confirmed. The patient had travelled from [[London]] to [[Antigua]] before arriving in Montserrat. On the 13 March the authorities had notified that a COVID-19 patient had been discovered on that flight and subsequently all passengers were quarantined and tested.<ref name=\"first\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/first-case-of-new-coronavirus-covid-19-confirmed-in-montserrat/|title=FIRST CASE OF NEW CORONAVIRUS (COVID-19) CONFIRMED IN MONTSERRAT|access-date=28 April 2020|website=Government of Montserrat}}</ref><ref name=\"WOMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) - Worldometer |website=www.worldometers.info}}</ref> \n\nOn 23 March, the second case was confirmed. The patient had no travel history and was the first case of [[community spread]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.ms/second-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-on-montserrat |title=Second Case of Coronavirus confirmed on Montserrat}} ''Government of Montserrat''</ref> \n\nOn 26 March, three more cases were confirmed to be positive bringing the total to five cases of COVID-19 on the island of Montserrat.<ref name=\"gov.ms\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.ms/statement-by-minister-of-health-social-services-hon-charles-t-kirnon/ |title=STATEMENT BY MINISTER OF HEALTH & SOCIAL SERVICES \u2013 HON. CHARLES T. KIRNON}} ''Government of Montserrat''</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 7 April, the number of cases had increased to eight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/positive-covid-19-cases-on-montserrat-increase-to-eight/|title=POSITIVE COVID-19 CASES ON MONTSERRAT INCREASE TO EIGHT|access-date=28 April 2020|website=Government of Montserrat}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April, the first death related to Covid-19 on Montserrat, that of a 92-year female, was sadly annnounced.<ref name=\"first_death\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/first-covid-19-related-death-recorded-on-montserrat/|title=First COVID-19 Related Death Recorded on Montserrat \u2013 Ministry of Health Statement \u00bb Government of Montserrat|website=www.gov.ms|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive measures==\n* 24 February: Travel restriction for China (including Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan), Japan, Malaysia, Singapore, Republic of Korea, Thailand and Iran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/montserrats-minister-of-health-issues-travel-advisory-due-to-the-current-outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease/|title=MONTSERRAT\u2019S MINISTER OF HEALTH ISSUES TRAVEL ADVISORY DUE TO THE CURRENT OUTBREAK OF CORONAVIRUS DISEASE|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 26 February: Travel restriction extended to Northern Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/montserrats-travel-advisory-due-to-coronavirus-disease-updated-to-include-northern-italy/|title=MONTSERRAT\u2019S TRAVEL ADVISORY DUE TO CORONAVIRUS DISEASE UPDATED TO INCLUDE NORTHERN ITALY|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 14 March: Schools are closed and gatherings over 50 people are prohibited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/government-of-montserrat-restricts-gatherings-of-more-than-50-persons-closes-schools-covid-19-update/|title=GOVERNMENT OF MONTSERRAT RESTRICTS GATHERINGS OF MORE THAN 50 PERSONS & CLOSES SCHOOLS \u2013 COVID 19 UPDATE|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref> Visits of hospitals and senior citizens homes are prohibited. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/visits-prohibited-at-the-hospital-and-senior-citizens-homes/|title=VISITS PROHIBITED AT THE HOSPITAL AND SENIOR CITIZENS HOMES|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 21 March: Gatherings over 25 are prohibited. Mandatory 14 day quarantine for travellers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/new-covid-19-measures-by-government-of-montserrat/|title=NEW COVID-19 MEASURES BY GOVERNMENT OF MONTSERRAT|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 25 March: Gatherings over 4 are prohibited. [[Curfew]] will be instituted between 19:00 and 05:00. Non-essential travel is prohibited. Non-residents are banned to enter by plane or ship. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/public-health-order-with-new-covid-19-measures-takes-effect-at-6pm-on-march-26/|title=PUBLIC HEALTH ORDER WITH NEW COVID-19 MEASURES TAKES EFFECT AT 6PM ON MARCH 26|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 28 March: 24 hour curfew from 28 March until 14 April. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/24-hour-curfew-until-april-14-among-new-measures-announced-by-government/|title=24 HOUR CURFEW UNTIL APRIL 14 AMONG NEW MEASURES ANNOUNCED BY GOVERNMENT|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 9 April: 7 day complete shutdown will come into effect and the curfew is extended to 30 April. On 11 and 12 April people will be allowed to shop for essential goods in four groups based on their last name. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/7-day-complete-shutdown-among-new-government-measures-to-contain-covid-19/|title=7-DAY COMPLETE SHUTDOWN AMONG NEW GOVERNMENT MEASURES TO CONTAIN COVID-19|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 17 April: Shutdown extended to until 1 May. Between 20 and 22 April people will be allowed to shop for essential goods based on their last name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/shutdown-extended-three-days-allowed-for-shopping/|title=SHUTDOWN EXTENDED\u2014 THREE DAYS ALLOWED FOR SHOPPING|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Montserrat|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Caribbean|Montserrat]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in British Overseas Territories|Montserrat]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Montserrat]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Montserrat}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Montserrat\n| map1 = \n| places = \n| legend1 =\n| map2 = \n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Montserrat]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 18 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=18|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| confirmed_cases = 11<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/montserrat-goes-second-week-with-no-new-cases-of-covid-19/|title=MONTSERRAT GOES SECOND WEEK WITH NO NEW CASES OF COVID-19|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref> (2020-04-25)\n| suspected_cases =\n| recovery_cases = 2\n| deaths = 1\n| total_ili =\n| website = [http://www.gov.ms gov.ms]\n}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] in Montserrat''' is part of the ongoing global [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|viral pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), which was confirmed to have reached the [[British Overseas Territory]] of [[Montserrat]] on 17 March 2020.<ref name=\"first\"/>. The first death occurred on 24 April 2020.<ref name=\"first_death\"/>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" />\n\nThe island had a population of 4,649 people in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/FINAL-REPORT-KEY-FINDINGS-CENSUS-LABOUR-FORCE-SURVEY-2018-.pdf|title=MONTSERRAT STATISTICS DEPARTMENT LABOUR FORCE CENSUS|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref> Testing for Covid-19 is being performed by the [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/positive-covid-19-cases-on-montserrat-increase-to-eight/|title=POSITIVE COVID-19 CASES ON MONTSERRAT INCREASE TO EIGHT|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===March 2020===\nOn 18 March, the first case in Montserrat was confirmed. The patient had travelled from [[London]] to [[Antigua]] before arriving in Montserrat. On the 13 March the authorities had notified that a COVID-19 patient had been discovered on that flight and subsequently all passengers were quarantined and tested.<ref name=\"first\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/first-case-of-new-coronavirus-covid-19-confirmed-in-montserrat/|title=FIRST CASE OF NEW CORONAVIRUS (COVID-19) CONFIRMED IN MONTSERRAT|access-date=28 April 2020|website=Government of Montserrat}}</ref><ref name=\"WOMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) - Worldometer |website=www.worldometers.info}}</ref> \n\nOn 23 March, the second case was confirmed. The patient had no travel history and was the first case of [[community spread]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.ms/second-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-on-montserrat |title=Second Case of Coronavirus confirmed on Montserrat}} ''Government of Montserrat''</ref> \n\nOn 26 March, three more cases were confirmed to be positive bringing the total to five cases of COVID-19 on the island of Montserrat.<ref name=\"gov.ms\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.ms/statement-by-minister-of-health-social-services-hon-charles-t-kirnon/ |title=STATEMENT BY MINISTER OF HEALTH & SOCIAL SERVICES \u2013 HON. CHARLES T. KIRNON}} ''Government of Montserrat''</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 7 April, the number of cases had increased to eight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/positive-covid-19-cases-on-montserrat-increase-to-eight/|title=POSITIVE COVID-19 CASES ON MONTSERRAT INCREASE TO EIGHT|access-date=28 April 2020|website=Government of Montserrat}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April, the first death related to Covid-19 on Montserrat, that of a 92-year female, was sadly annnounced.<ref name=\"first_death\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/first-covid-19-related-death-recorded-on-montserrat/|title=First COVID-19 Related Death Recorded on Montserrat \u2013 Ministry of Health Statement \u00bb Government of Montserrat|website=www.gov.ms|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive measures==\n* 24 February: Travel restriction for China (including Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan), Japan, Malaysia, Singapore, Republic of Korea, Thailand and Iran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/montserrats-minister-of-health-issues-travel-advisory-due-to-the-current-outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease/|title=MONTSERRAT\u2019S MINISTER OF HEALTH ISSUES TRAVEL ADVISORY DUE TO THE CURRENT OUTBREAK OF CORONAVIRUS DISEASE|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 26 February: Travel restriction extended to Northern Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/montserrats-travel-advisory-due-to-coronavirus-disease-updated-to-include-northern-italy/|title=MONTSERRAT\u2019S TRAVEL ADVISORY DUE TO CORONAVIRUS DISEASE UPDATED TO INCLUDE NORTHERN ITALY|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 14 March: Schools are closed and gatherings over 50 people are prohibited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/government-of-montserrat-restricts-gatherings-of-more-than-50-persons-closes-schools-covid-19-update/|title=GOVERNMENT OF MONTSERRAT RESTRICTS GATHERINGS OF MORE THAN 50 PERSONS & CLOSES SCHOOLS \u2013 COVID 19 UPDATE|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref> Visits of hospitals and senior citizens homes are prohibited. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/visits-prohibited-at-the-hospital-and-senior-citizens-homes/|title=VISITS PROHIBITED AT THE HOSPITAL AND SENIOR CITIZENS HOMES|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 21 March: Gatherings over 25 are prohibited. Mandatory 14 day quarantine for travellers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/new-covid-19-measures-by-government-of-montserrat/|title=NEW COVID-19 MEASURES BY GOVERNMENT OF MONTSERRAT|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 25 March: Gatherings over 4 are prohibited. [[Curfew]] will be instituted between 19:00 and 05:00. Non-essential travel is prohibited. Non-residents are banned to enter by plane or ship. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/public-health-order-with-new-covid-19-measures-takes-effect-at-6pm-on-march-26/|title=PUBLIC HEALTH ORDER WITH NEW COVID-19 MEASURES TAKES EFFECT AT 6PM ON MARCH 26|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 28 March: 24 hour curfew from 28 March until 14 April. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/24-hour-curfew-until-april-14-among-new-measures-announced-by-government/|title=24 HOUR CURFEW UNTIL APRIL 14 AMONG NEW MEASURES ANNOUNCED BY GOVERNMENT|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 9 April: 7 day complete shutdown will come into effect and the curfew is extended to 30 April. On 11 and 12 April people will be allowed to shop for essential goods in four groups based on their last name. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/7-day-complete-shutdown-among-new-government-measures-to-contain-covid-19/|title=7-DAY COMPLETE SHUTDOWN AMONG NEW GOVERNMENT MEASURES TO CONTAIN COVID-19|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 17 April: Shutdown extended to until 1 May. Between 20 and 22 April people will be allowed to shop for essential goods based on their last name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.ms/shutdown-extended-three-days-allowed-for-shopping/|title=SHUTDOWN EXTENDED\u2014 THREE DAYS ALLOWED FOR SHOPPING|website=Government of Montserrat|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Montserrat|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Caribbean|Montserrat]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in British Overseas Territories|Montserrat]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Montserrat]]\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "+map", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Montserrat"}
